# Package management — `apt` & `dnf`

A **package manager** downloads from a repo, resolves dependencies, installs cleanly, removes later. Two families:

- **Debian/Ubuntu** — `.deb`, **`apt`** (`dpkg` underneath)
- **RHEL/Fedora** — `.rpm`, **`dnf`** (`rpm` underneath)

| Task | apt | dnf |
|---|---|---|
| refresh | `apt update` | *(automatic)* |
| upgrade all | `apt upgrade` | `dnf upgrade` |
| install / remove | `apt install`/`remove` | `dnf install`/`remove` |
| owns a file | `dpkg -S` | `dnf provides` |
| clean orphans | `apt autoremove` | `dnf autoremove` |

⚠️ **`update` vs `upgrade`:** `update` refreshes the *list* (installs nothing); `upgrade` installs newer versions. **Always `apt update` first.** dnf refreshes automatically + has `dnf history undo N`.

Got a `.deb`/`.rpm` file? Use the high-level tool so deps resolve: `apt install ./pkg.deb`. Low-level `dpkg -i`/`rpm -i` skip dependencies.
